277
00:17:45,192 --> 00:17:46,159
Can we do anything?

278
00:17:46,294 --> 00:17:47,454
I got to go.

279
00:17:48,930 --> 00:17:51,023
Mr and Mrs Archibald.

280
00:17:51,165 --> 00:17:52,325
I'm Rebecca Payne, Hospital Director.

281
00:17:53,367 --> 00:17:54,095
Hi there.

282
00:17:54,235 --> 00:17:54,894
It's nice to meet you.

283
00:17:55,036 --> 00:17:56,503
This is Dr Turner, head of Cardiology 

284
00:17:56,637 --> 00:17:57,626
and Michael's doctor.

285
00:17:57,772 --> 00:17:59,637
How do you do?

286
00:17:59,840 --> 00:18:01,467
Good. My wife.

287
00:18:01,842 --> 00:18:03,241
How's our boy doing?

288
00:18:04,445 --> 00:18:05,810
Please sit down.

289
00:18:28,135 --> 00:18:30,763
This x-ray shows a normal nine-year-old's heart.

290
00:18:31,172 --> 00:18:34,198
This x-ray is that of your son Michael.

291
00:18:35,776 --> 00:18:38,973
There are septal defects 

292
00:18:39,113 --> 00:18:41,479
here, here, and here

293
00:18:41,616 --> 00:18:44,107
which have induced myopathy, resulting pulmonary edema,

294
00:18:44,251 --> 00:18:46,151
and malignant ventricular ectopy.

295
00:18:46,420 --> 00:18:47,409
Michael's heart is approximately

296
00:18:47,555 --> 00:18:50,581
three times larger than normal size.

297
00:18:50,725 --> 00:18:51,817
I'm sorry.

298
00:18:53,794 --> 00:18:54,886
I didn't understand what you said.

299
00:18:55,029 --> 00:18:57,327
Could you put that in layman terms?

300
00:18:57,565 --> 00:18:58,657
Basically, 

301
00:18:58,799 --> 00:19:01,927
there's not enough blood being pumped by Michael's heart,

302
00:19:02,069 --> 00:19:04,594
so it backs up in the lungs

303
00:19:04,739 --> 00:19:06,263
like a sponge getting wet.

304
00:19:06,941 --> 00:19:10,502
His heart is trying, but it's working too hard.

305
00:19:10,778 --> 00:19:13,747
What, does he need an operation, or...

306
00:19:15,349 --> 00:19:18,113
We're considerably beyond corrective surgery, Mr and Mrs Archibald.

307
00:19:18,252 --> 00:19:21,050
Mike's heart is useless.

308
00:19:21,722 --> 00:19:24,520
He's going to need a transplant or he's going to die.

309
00:19:27,261 --> 00:19:29,889
Wait a second. There are other options.

310
00:19:30,031 --> 00:19:30,963
What options?

311
00:19:31,899 --> 00:19:34,766
To do nothing. Medicate him.

312
00:19:34,935 --> 00:19:36,425
Make him feel as comfortable as possible.

313
00:19:36,570 --> 00:19:39,198
You're going to have to start thinking about quality of life now.

314
00:19:39,340 --> 00:19:40,967
I don't understand.

315
00:19:41,942 --> 00:19:43,534
We were just with him 

316
00:19:43,678 --> 00:19:45,942
and he seemed fine.

317
00:19:46,080 --> 00:19:48,708
He's going to seem fine, but as his heart gets worse,

318
00:19:48,849 --> 00:19:51,113
he will become increasingly fatigued,

319
00:19:51,352 --> 00:19:53,115
and he will sleep more and more,

320
00:19:53,988 --> 00:19:56,149
until one day he will fall asleep,

321
00:19:57,191 --> 00:19:58,852
and he won't wake up.

322
00:20:00,561 --> 00:20:02,051
I know this is difficult,

323
00:20:02,196 --> 00:20:04,528
but you have to face the fact

324
00:20:04,665 --> 00:20:06,633
that your son may not live much longer.

325
00:20:06,767 --> 00:20:10,294
You might want to make it a happy time, say good-bye.

326
00:20:11,572 --> 00:20:13,005
God.

327
00:20:13,240 --> 00:20:16,141
Transplantation is a high-risk operation.

328
00:20:16,277 --> 00:20:19,212
You could lose your son on that table.

329
00:20:21,982 --> 00:20:25,975
You might not want to take that chance.

330
00:20:30,858 --> 00:20:32,382
If he doesn't have the surgery...

331
00:20:32,526 --> 00:20:33,823
If he doesn't have the surgery, how long would he live?

332
00:20:33,961 --> 00:20:34,791
Not long. 

333
00:20:34,929 --> 00:20:36,396
Months, weeks.

334
00:20:37,298 --> 00:20:38,731
Days.

335
00:20:40,367 --> 00:20:43,803
Come on. All right.

336
00:20:43,938 --> 00:20:45,371
Come on, now.

337
00:20:53,280 --> 00:20:54,907
I'm sorry.

338
00:20:56,917 --> 00:20:58,509
This is a lot.

339
00:21:14,268 --> 00:21:15,030
All right.

340
00:21:19,774 --> 00:21:22,038
If he was your son, what would you do?

341
00:21:23,978 --> 00:21:25,946
I'd do the transplant, absolutely.

342
00:21:26,080 --> 00:21:27,069
Okay.

343
00:21:28,215 --> 00:21:29,409
Okay? 

344
00:21:31,552 --> 00:21:34,248
Let's do that. Let's do it.

345
00:21:37,892 --> 00:21:40,918
First we've got to get Mike's name on the organ recipient list.

346
00:21:41,061 --> 00:21:43,962
He's B-positive, so his name should go right to the top.

347
00:21:44,098 --> 00:21:45,360
It's not so simple.

348
00:21:45,499 --> 00:21:46,989
There are other considerations before

349
00:21:47,134 --> 00:21:49,102
a recipient can be placed on a donor list.

350
00:21:49,236 --> 00:21:52,672
Transplant surgery is very expensive.

351
00:21:53,140 --> 00:21:54,903
In most cases, prohibitively so.

352
00:21:55,042 --> 00:21:56,475
We got insurance, 

353
00:21:56,610 --> 00:21:58,271
major medical.He's covered.

354
00:21:58,412 --> 00:22:00,778
We've already checked with your carrier, Mr Archibald.

355
00:22:01,081 --> 00:22:03,982
There are no provisions in your policy for a procedure of this magnitude.

356
00:22:04,118 --> 00:22:06,916
That's a mistake.

357
00:22:07,054 --> 00:22:08,521
Not that you're making a mistake.

358
00:22:08,656 --> 00:22:11,557
I'm just saying that I'm insured. 

359
00:22:11,692 --> 00:22:13,159
My son's covered.

360
00:22:13,561 --> 00:22:14,687
Mrs Archibald, 

361
